Maybe we want to limit them to some things that are more

00:04:45.700 --> 00:04:46.540
positive.

00:04:46.550 --> 00:04:50.830
So, generally, what if we attach logic to record authorization

00:04:50.830 --> 00:04:51.000
?

00:04:51.010 --> 00:04:59.140
If we're talking about signatures, then the limits are that

00:04:59.140 --> 00:05:04.460
what I've mentioned, which is you just can say that

00:05:04.460 --> 00:05:06.780
the deed agreed for something to be published.

00:05:06.790 --> 00:05:12.140
But with logic, you can say the deed ran this program

00:05:12.140 --> 00:05:17.100
before publishing and this is a strong guarantee that you can get

00:05:17.100 --> 00:05:17.240
.

00:05:17.250 --> 00:05:24.050
You can do that with signatures if you trust the signer

00:05:24.050 --> 00:05:24.240
.

00:05:24.250 --> 00:05:29.080
So, you know, if you trust the people who run

00:05:29.080 --> 00:05:34.740
the deed to run this program for you or run this program

00:05:34.740 --> 00:05:37.690
by themselves, then you can get this guarantee.

00:05:37.710 --> 00:05:41.520
But in a big network with lots of people, sometimes in

00:05:41.520 --> 00:05:47.070
adversarial scenarios, you want some third-party guarantee that

00:05:47.070 --> 00:05:47.900
this program ran.

00:05:47.910 --> 00:05:51.240
And this acts as a filter to the operations you perform.

00:05:51.250 --> 00:05:57.150
So, now let's talk about what trusted execution environments are

00:05:57.150 --> 00:05:57.420
.

00:05:57.420 --> 00:05:59.250
It's a bit of a mouthful, at least for

00:05:59.270 --> 00:05:59.520
me.

00:05:59.530 --> 00:06:06.940
Trusted execution environments or TEs are special kind of hardware

00:06:06.950 --> 00:06:11.290
that are built in a way that allows you to get a

00:06:11.290 --> 00:06:13.560
guarantee of what's running inside it.

00:06:13.570 --> 00:06:20.690
Specifically, these machines or these machines with special security chips allow

00:06:20.690 --> 00:06:25.230
you to measure, get some measurements of what's running inside

00:06:25.300 --> 00:06:25.790
it.

00:06:25.810 --> 00:06:29.820
So, you can get the guarantee of what code is running

00:06:29.820 --> 00:06:30.820
inside them.

00:06:30.830 --> 00:06:33.520
You can do that really all the way down.

00:06:33.530 --> 00:06:37.610
You can do that to the base OS that's running inside

00:06:37.610 --> 00:06:38.140
the TE.

00:06:38.150 --> 00:06:43.820
You can say what binary is running there.

00:06:43.830 --> 00:06:48.360
And even more, you can even get a more powerful guarantee

00:06:48.360 --> 00:06:50.880
, which is even what source code is running there.

00:06:51.830 --> 00:06:54.330
in the way that, let's say that you have some

00:06:54.330 --> 00:06:57.100
source code published on GitHub, Tangle, whatever.

00:06:57.110 --> 00:07:02.040
You can build it in a special way that is called a

00:07:02.040 --> 00:07:05.620
reproducible build that gets you the same binary each time.

00:07:05.630 --> 00:07:10.190
You can then check that this binary is what's running in

00:07:10.190 --> 00:07:10.900
the TE.

00:07:12.270 --> 00:07:17.310
One downside of TE is that it adds some trust assumption on

00:07:17.310 --> 00:07:21.580
the TE provider or the TE manufacturer more correctly.

00:07:21.590 --> 00:07:25.700
Concretely, you need to trust that the TE manufacturer

00:07:25.710 --> 00:07:31.870
built the trusted platform in a way that is robust, that

00:07:31.870 --> 00:07:35.100
does give you this guarantee that these measurements are correct.

00:07:35.110 --> 00:07:37.640
That's unavoidable, but that's the trust assumption

00:07:37.640 --> 00:07:38.480
that you would have to make.

00:07:40.910 --> 00:07:46.930
Okay, so what we want to talk about is how these

00:07:46.930 --> 00:07:51.340
two areas connect, how at Proto that has keys connect

00:07:51.350 --> 00:07:52.100
to TEs.

00:07:52.110 --> 00:07:55.440
So there is this concept called key encumbrance.

00:07:55.450 --> 00:08:01.600
And key encumbrance means a public-private keeper

00:08:01.610 --> 00:08:05.830
for, let's say, digital signatures where the private key

00:08:05.850 --> 00:08:07.650
is never known to the public.

00:08:07.670 --> 00:08:14.920
It is only generated inside this TE and the TE does not

00:08:14.920 --> 00:08:17.420
provide a way for you to extract it outside.

00:08:17.430 --> 00:08:22.530
What we can do now, we can think about, okay

00:08:22.540 --> 00:08:26.250
, we have a TE that runs a specific program and we

00:08:26.250 --> 00:08:31.580
have a key that's locked inside it and will never be

00:08:31.580 --> 00:08:32.860
put outside.

00:08:34.470 --> 00:08:40.050
what if we add specific conditions under which signatures can be done

00:08:40.050 --> 00:08:40.220
.

00:08:40.230 --> 00:08:43.780
So basically what we can do is we can tie a key

00:08:43.780 --> 00:08:45.160
to a specific program.

00:08:45.170 --> 00:08:49.300
And the really nice property that you get with this kind of

00:08:49.300 --> 00:08:55.100
setup is that you can convert logic to digital signatures.

00:08:55.110 --> 00:08:57.720
And what I mean here is the following.

00:08:58.990 --> 00:09:03.660
let's say that you have the guarantee that, okay,

00:09:03.670 --> 00:09:05.340
there is a TE provider that you trust.

00:09:05.350 --> 00:09:09.900
You then have a key that is generated inside this TE.

00:09:09.910 --> 00:09:15.690
Then you have the program that you know what are the conditions

00:09:15.710 --> 00:09:19.080
it would sign under that uses that specific key.

00:09:21.190 --> 00:09:27.760
And you get this kind of chain of verifiability where

00:09:27.760 --> 00:09:33.480
you only need to verify this attestation or this proof

00:09:33.490 --> 00:09:38.000
that this key came from a valid TE once.

00:09:38.010 --> 00:09:42.300
And once you do that you can just verify signatures.

00:09:42.310 --> 00:09:44.700
You don't have to do anything else anymore.

00:09:44.710 --> 00:09:53.020
So this is the kind of minimal overhead

00:09:53.030 --> 00:09:57.410
that you can have while still getting a very powerful guarantee.

00:09:57.430 --> 00:10:02.100
So this is this verifiability all the way down.

00:10:02.110 --> 00:10:08.880
You usually have from this TE manufacturer a root certificate that cert

00:10:08.880 --> 00:10:10.980
ifies this is the correct hardware.

00:10:10.990 --> 00:10:13.820
This is valid hardware that is secure.

00:10:13.890 --> 00:10:18.200
You then have proof of what program is running.

00:10:18.960 --> 00:10:21.580
So you know this is the expected logic that runs there.

00:10:21.590 --> 00:10:29.180
And then you know that whenever the TE produces signatures the logic

00:10:29.180 --> 00:10:32.920
agrees with whatever you wanted to run there.

00:10:32.930 --> 00:10:38.130
Now maybe you can think about okay, but that means I

00:10:38.130 --> 00:10:42.550
now have to start verifying these weird TE proofs all

00:10:42.550 --> 00:10:42.940
the time.

00:10:42.950 --> 00:10:44.280
No.

00:10:44.290 --> 00:10:47.820
Because you can maybe assume that some people verify them.

00:10:47.830 --> 00:10:53.360
As long as enough people in the world go ahead and verify

00:10:53.360 --> 00:10:58.840
TE proofs about these keys other people relays other actors

00:10:58.840 --> 00:11:00.520
in the network can just verify signatures.

